<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-763-484  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 763 484.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 16 1989 v23 n42 p111(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Weighing a system's worth. (Index Group Inc consultant RobertBarrett) (interview)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ludlum, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Index Group Inc consultant David Ludlum discusses methods ofmeasuring the potential value of computer systems to a company.andO;Cost-benefit analysis is the traditional method of evaluatinginformation systems, but tends to be distorted because manyinformation-systems benefits are intangible.andP;  Theinformation-systems (IS) manager needs to build a business casebut should not be the one selling the project.andP;  Groups ofexecutives should sponsor projects that go across divisionboundaries, tying system benefits to the firm's overall businessinitiatives.andP;  Quantifying benefits and agreeing on projectedbenefits is important; ultimately, only end users can trulydetermine how beneficial a new system will be.andP;  IS is no longer apurely technical organization, but has become a function tied intothe strategies of the entire company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISSystem SelectionPurchasesManagement of EDPInterview.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Robert Barrett. (portrait)Person:    Barrett, Robert (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>